<div id="review_3341122919" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3341122919" />
    <a title="Dawn C" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14948447-dawn-c"><img alt="Dawn C" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1535435406p2/14948447.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3341122919?book_show_action=true">Dec 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dawn C" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dawn C" href="/user/show/14948447-dawn-c">Dawn C</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14948447-dawn-c?shelf=media-physical">media-physical</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3341122919" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5630421044034515244">This is a difficult one to both rate and form an opinion on. It reads mostly like a cartoon, where everything that happens is completely unlikely and the things our heroes do and survive are completely unrealistic. The story itself is bonkers and told like an adventure with obstacles the main characters have to face and puzzles they have to solve. It&apos;s full of deus ex machina, people they need magially happen to be there, and things they need they have right at hand. Young Ox, one of the protago</span>
  <span id="freeText5630421044034515244" style="display:none">This is a difficult one to both rate and form an opinion on. It reads mostly like a cartoon, where everything that happens is completely unlikely and the things our heroes do and survive are completely unrealistic. The story itself is bonkers and told like an adventure with obstacles the main characters have to face and puzzles they have to solve. It's full of deus ex machina, people they need magially happen to be there, and things they need they have right at hand. Young Ox, one of the protagonists, can run across half of China carrying an old man on his back like a horse and not break a sweat. They can survive falls from cliffs, lava, drowning, flying and an abundance of other craziness. It's farcical with slapstick humor all around.<br /><br />It's entirely consistently written, though, it's all on purpose - and absolutely not my cup of tea.<br /><br />However, the last 30 pages made reading it worth it all, in fact it got me so good I got goosebumps. That reveal was perfectly delivered and worth 4 ⭐️ in and of itself, but the rest of the book is a 2 for me, so I will park it here in the neutral zone at 3.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5630421044034515244" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


